  [33m> Write[0m(file_path='/Users/nomind/Code/duh/benchmarks/benchmark-2-ratelimit/worktrees/duh-gemini-3.1/README.md', content='# Ratelimit\n\nA distributed rate limiter as a standalone Python package. It supports multiple algorithms, interchangeable backends, and integrates smoothly into ASGI web applications.\n\n## Installation\n\nYou can install this package by dropping the `ratelimit` directory into your project.\n\n```bash\npip install redis\n```\n\n## Features\n\n- **Algorithms**: Token Bucket and Sliding Window Counter.\n- **Backends**: In-Memory (for single-node/tests) and Redis (for distributed deployments, uses atomic Lua scripts to prevent lost-update races).\n- **Integrations**: Function decorator and ASGI Middleware (FastAPI/Starlette compatible).\n\n## Usage\n\n### 1. Direct Usage\n\n```python\nfrom ratelimit import InMemoryBackend, TokenBucketLimiter\n\nbackend = InMemoryBackend()\n# Capacity of 10 requests, refills 2 requests per second\nlimiter = TokenBucketLimiter(backend, capacity=10, refill_rate=2.0)\n\ndecision = limiter.enforce("user_123")\nif decision.allowed:\n    print(f"Success! Remaining: {decision.remaining}")\nelse:\n    print(f"Rate limited. Retry after {decision.retry_after_ms}ms")\n```\n\n### 2. Distributed Usage with Redis\n\n```python\nimport redis\nfrom ratelimit import RedisBackend, SlidingWindowLimiter\n\nclient = redis.Redis(host=\'localhost\', port=6379)\nbackend = RedisBackend(client)\n\n# Max 5 requests per 10-second window\nlimiter = SlidingWindowLimiter(backend, capacity=5, window_size_ms=10000)\n\ndecision = limiter.enforce("user_456")\n```\n\n### 3. Function Decorator\n\n```python\nfrom ratelimit import rate_limit, InMemoryBackend, TokenBucketLimiter\n\nbackend = InMemoryBackend()\nlimiter = TokenBucketLimiter(backend, capacity=5, refill_rate=1.0)\n\n@rate_limit(limiter, key_fn=lambda user_id: f"user:{user_id}")\ndef sensitive_operation(user_id: str):\n    return "Data!"\n\n# Raises RateLimitExceeded if limit is hit\n```\n\n### 4. ASGI Middleware (FastAPI / Starlette)\n\n```python\nfrom fastapi import FastAPI\nfrom ratelimit import RateLimitMiddleware, InMemoryBackend, TokenBucketLimiter\n\napp = FastAPI()\nbackend = InMemoryBackend()\nlimiter = TokenBucketLimiter(backend, capacity=100, refill_rate=10.0)\n\n# Extracts client IP to use as the rate limit key\napp.add_middleware(\n    RateLimitMiddleware, \n    limiter=limiter, \n    key_fn=lambda scope: scope.get("client", ["default"])[0]\n)\n\n@app.get("/")\nasync def root():\n    return {"message": "Hello World"}\n```\n\n## Operational Caveats\n\n- **Clock Skew**: In distributed mode, this library relies on the Redis server clock (`TIME` command inside Lua script) to guarantee precise and synchronized rate enforcement across multiple application nodes.\n- **Failure Modes**: The `RateLimitMiddleware` implements a **fail-open** strategy. If the backend (e.g., Redis) is unreachable or times out, the rate limiter will silently permit the request to ensure your application remains available during infrastructure degradation.\n- **Redis Requirement**: The `RedisBackend` requires Redis >= 3.2 because it relies on the `EVAL` command with `TIME` capabilities.\n')
  [33m> Read[0m(file_path='/Users/nomind/Code/duh/benchmarks/benchmark-2-ratelimit/worktrees/duh-gemini-3.1/tests/test_hypothesis.py')
  [33m> Edit[0m(new_string='## Choice of Sliding Window Implementation\nWe chose **Sliding-Window-Log** over **Sliding-Window-Counter**.\n- **Sliding-Window-Log**: Records the exact timestamp of every request. Tradeoff: perfectly accurate, guaranteeing that no more than `capacity` requests are ever granted in *any* continuous window of length `period`. Memory usage and processing time scale with the number of requests (O(N) per window), but for typical rate limits it is manageable.\n- **Sliding-Window-Counter**: Divides the window into fixed sub-windows and approximates the count. Tradeoff: uses O(1) memory per key, much lower overhead, but can allow bursts of up to 1.5x capacity in adversarial overlapping windows.\n- **Decision**: The Log approach is chosen because strict enforcement of the limit over any time window is a hard invariant for our system, prioritizing correctness over raw constant-time performance.', file_path='/Users/nomind/Code/duh/benchmarks/benchmark-2-ratelimit/worktrees/duh-gemini-3.1/docs/adr/ADR-001-rate-limiter-design.md')
  [33m> Edit[0m(file_path='/Users/nomind/Code/duh/benchmarks/benchmark-2-ratelimit/worktrees/duh-gemini-3.1/docs/design.md', old_string='Out of the box, it supports Token Bucket and Sliding Window Counter algorithms')
  [33m> Write[0m(content="import time\nimport threading\nfrom typing import Dict, Tuple, List\nfrom ..types import Decision\nfrom .base import Backend\n\nclass InMemoryBackend(Backend):\n    def __init__(self):\n        self._lock = threading.Lock()\n        # Token bucket: key -> (tokens, last_refill_ts_ms)\n        self._tb_state: Dict[str, Tuple[float, int]] = {}\n        # Sliding window log: key -> list of timestamps\n        self._sw_state: Dict[str, List[int]] = {}\n\n    def token_bucket(self, key: str, capacity: int, refill_rate: float, cost: int) -> Decision:\n        now_ms = int(time.time() * 1000)\n        \n        with self._lock:\n            tokens, last_refill_ts_ms = self._tb_state.get(key, (float(capacity), now_ms))\n            \n            elapsed_ms = now_ms - last_refill_ts_ms\n            new_tokens = min(capacity, tokens + (elapsed_ms / 1000.0) * refill_rate)\n            \n            if new_tokens >= cost:\n                new_tokens -= cost\n                self._tb_state[key] = (new_tokens, now_ms)\n                allowed = True\n            else:\n                self._tb_state[key] = (new_tokens, now_ms)\n                allowed = False\n                \n            remaining = int(new_tokens)\n            if not allowed:\n                tokens_needed = cost - new_tokens\n                retry_after_ms = int((tokens_needed / refill_rate) * 1000) if refill_rate > 0 else 0\n            else:\n                retry_after_ms = 0\n                \n            time_to_full_ms = int(((capacity - new_tokens) / refill_rate) * 1000) if refill_rate > 0 else 0\n            reset_ts = now_ms + time_to_full_ms\n\n            return Decision(\n                allowed=allowed,\n                limit=capacity,\n                remaining=remaining,\n                retry_after_ms=retry_after_ms,\n                reset_ts=reset_ts\n            )\n\n    def sliding_window(self, key: str, capacity: int, window_size_ms: int, cost: int) -> Decision:\n        now_ms = int(time.time() * 1000)\n        cutoff_ms = now_ms - window_size_ms\n        \n        with self._lock:\n            log = self._sw_state.get(key, [])\n            # Evict old timestamps\n            log = [ts for ts in log if ts > cutoff_ms]\n            \n            count = sum(1 for _ in log)\n            allowed = (count + cost) <= capacity\n            \n            if allowed:\n                for _ in range(cost):\n                    log.append(now_ms)\n                self._sw_state[key] = log\n            else:\n                self._sw_state[key] = log\n                \n            remaining = max(0, capacity - count) if not allowed else max(0, capacity - (count + cost))\n            \n            if not allowed:\n                # Oldest timestamp that we need to wait for to free up 'cost' tokens\n                # Wait until the (count - capacity + cost)-th element falls out of the window\n                needed_evictions = (count + cost) - capacity\n                if needed_evictions > 0 and len(log) >= needed_evictions:\n                    oldest_to_evict = log[needed_evictions - 1]\n                    retry_after_ms = oldest_to_evict - cutoff_ms\n                else:\n                    retry_after_ms = window_size_ms\n            else:\n                retry_after_ms = 0\n                \n            # Reset when the newest element falls out\n            reset_ts = log[-1] + window_size_ms if log else now_ms\n\n            return Decision(\n                allowed=allowed,\n                limit=capacity,\n                remaining=remaining,\n                retry_after_ms=retry_after_ms,\n                reset_ts=reset_ts\n            )\n", file_path='/Users/nomind/Code/duh/benchmarks/benchmark-2-ratelimit/worktrees/duh-gemini-3.1/ratelimit/backends/memory.py')
  [33m> Edit[0m(new_string='SLIDING_WINDOW_LUA = """\nlocal key = KEYS[1]\nlocal capacity = tonumber(ARGV[1])\nlocal window_size_ms = tonumber(ARGV[2])\nlocal cost = tonumber(ARGV[3])\n\nlocal time_arr = redis.call(\'TIME\')\nlocal now_ms = tonumber(time_arr[1]) * 1000 + math.floor(tonumber(time_arr[2]) / 1000)\nlocal cutoff_ms = now_ms - window_size_ms\n\n-- Evict old elements\nredis.call(\'ZREMRANGEBYSCORE\', key, \'-inf\', cutoff_ms)\n\nlocal count = redis.call(\'ZCARD\', key)\nlocal allowed = 0\nlocal retry_after_ms = 0\nlocal reset_ts = now_ms\n\nif count + cost <= capacity then\n    allowed = 1\n    for i = 1, cost do\n        -- Use now_ms + a slight counter for unique elements if needed, but Redis 5.0 allows identical scores,\n        -- but sorted set needs unique members. We use now_ms..i as member.\n        redis.call(\'ZADD\', key, now_ms, now_ms .. \'_\' .. i)\n    end\n    count = count + cost\nelse\n    -- Find the timestamp that needs to be evicted to make room\n    local needed_evictions = (count + cost) - capacity\n    local elements = redis.call(\'ZRANGE\', key, needed_evictions - 1, needed_evictions - 1, \'WITHSCORES\')\n    if #elements >= 2 then\n        local oldest_to_evict_score = tonumber(elements[2])\n        retry_after_ms = oldest_to_evict_score - cutoff_ms\n    else\n        retry_after_ms = window_size_ms\n    end\nend\n\nredis.call(\'PEXPIRE\', key, window_size_ms)\n\n-- Get the latest score for reset_ts\nlocal latest = redis.call(\'ZREVRANGE\', key, 0, 0, \'WITHSCORES\')\nif #latest >= 2 then\n    reset_ts = tonumber(latest[2]) + window_size_ms\nend\n\nreturn {allowed, count, retry_after_ms, reset_ts}\n"""', file_path='/Users/nomind/Code/duh/benchmarks/benchmark-2-ratelimit/worktrees/duh-gemini-3.1/ratelimit/backends/redis.py')
  [33m> Edit[0m(old_string='    def sliding_window(self, key: str, capacity: int, window_size_ms: int, cost: int) -> Decision:\n        result = self.redis.eval(SLIDING_WINDOW_LUA, 1, key, capacity, window_size_ms, cost)\n        allowed_int, estimated_count, curr_start, now_ms = result\n        allowed = bool(allowed_int)\n        \n        remaining = max(0, capacity - estimated_count) if not allowed else max(0, capacity - (estimated_count + cost))\n        \n        if not allowed:\n            elapsed_in_window_ms = now_ms - curr_start\n            retry_after_ms = window_size_ms - elapsed_in_window_ms\n        else:\n            retry_after_ms = 0\n            \n        reset_ts = curr_start + window_size_ms\n\n        return Decision(\n            allowed=allowed,\n            limit=capacity,\n            remaining=remaining,\n            retry_after_ms=retry_after_ms,\n            reset_ts=reset_ts\n        )', new_string='    def sliding_window(self, key: str, capacity: int, window_size_ms: int, cost: int) -> Decision:\n        result = self.redis.eval(SLIDING_WINDOW_LUA, 1, key, capacity, window_size_ms, cost)\n        allowed_int, count, retry_after_ms, reset_ts = result\n        allowed = bool(allowed_int)\n        \n        remaining = max(0, capacity - count)\n\n        return Decision(\n            allowed=allowed,\n            limit=capacity,\n            remaining=remaining,\n            retry_after_ms=retry_after_ms,\n            reset_ts=reset_ts\n        )')
